At the end of the exchanges, the Prague Stock Exchange tipped into the negative
After the fall on Tuesday morning, the Prague stock exchange recovered its losses.
Transactions with <0xC4><0x8C>EZ stocks reached almost half of the usual daily exchanges.
On Tuesday, from the beginning of the exchange, the Prague Stock Exchange rebounded with its fall the day before, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in shares on Wall Street.
The reaction of the market to the outcome of the U.S. House of Representatives vote, which refused to adopt the stabilization plan for the U.S. financial sector, is thus also perceptible here.
Stocks fall in Asia
Asian stock markets experienced a dramatic decline on Tuesday, even though the indices succeeded, over the course of the day, to erase some of the losses.
The Hong Kong Stock Exchange Hang Seng Index lost four percent during trading, but later erased some of the losses and reduced the decline to nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index following the Chinese stock movement on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange lost 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
The shares of the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but ultimately we managed to reduce the losses to 4.3 percent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
"Hesitation about the U.S. bailout will affect financial markets around the world," noted Joseph Yam, head of Hong Kong's monetary office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it establishes its monetary policy itself, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, U.S. lawmakers should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there would be a risk that other countries would be affected.
The bloodbath of American stocks
On Monday, the U.S. House of Representatives rejected the proposed financial system support, to which it should have devoted up to $700 billion (nearly K<0xC4><0x8D> 12 billion).
Legislators thus denied the call for support for President George Bush's bill.
According to Bush, the project should solve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, U.S. stocks experienced a bloodbath and major stock indices saw the biggest drop in the last 20 years.
The Dow Jones Index lost nearly seven percent, having last seen a fall of such magnitude in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it became apparent that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress gives way: US government can inject $700 billion into banks
The leaders of the U.S. Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of the financial aid agreement to the U.S. financial system.
It will be put to the vote at the beginning of next week.
U.S. lawmakers made a turning point in talks over the adoption of a bailout in the form of $700 billion in financial assistance to the U.S. financial system.
However, success is not certain.
Indeed, before they can publish the final version of the law and put it to the vote, Congressmen must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The financial system support plan will be discussed Monday in the House of Representatives.
Barney Frank, the chairman of the House’s banking and financial regulation committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to sources, on Wednesday at the earliest, the plan should a priori be put to the vote in the Senate.
According to economists, the announcement that the bailout will be adopted should be a major first psychological factor in reviving financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms by which market aid can be effective, a "disillusionment" will follow.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have settled our divergent views on the shape of the market stabilization package," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could be held as early as Sunday.
On Saturday night, lawmakers met with U.S. Finance Minister Henry Paulson to give the bottom of the government a final form.
It is expected to buy back from financial companies the unsellable real estate assets that cause financial firms to suffer considerable losses and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
“We are about to agree on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
We still need to pursue this market recovery plan, but I think we are," Paulson said.
A signal for Asian exchanges
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on falling stock markets.
According to the Democratic senator did escape Harry Reid, the lawmakers are making sure that Congress comes to a final agreement as early as Sunday.
They want to calm investors ahead of the start of trading in Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where the congressional decision could influence Monday’s trading.
At the moment, however, it is impossible to say with certainty when the two Houses of Congress will vote, nor whether the negotiations are likely to be blocked, at the last moment, by this or that problem.
Legislators hope that it will be adopted in the coming days.
However, the law will still undergo many changes.
The total amount allocated to the system should be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wished, should be available as soon as possible.
But if Congress will feel that the program is not fulfilling its function, it has the possibility to block the granting of the remaining amount, following two steps: first an additional $100 billion, and then, finally, $350 billion.
Bush welcomes progress in negotiations
Although the president can veto this decision, Congress has the opportunity to put it in the minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which was to obtain finance for the redemption of bad real estate securities, whose value fell, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are not able to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
“All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
U.S. President George Bush himself is pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated “the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.”
Limitation of Golden Parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chair Christopher Dodd, Chief Negotiator, says legislators have agreed on responsibility for the financial program, protection of contributors from losses, the rebate agreement, and the timeline of the plan.
The new law also provides for the limitation of such golden parachutes for the directors of the companies participating in the program and establishes a committee, which will oversee the fund.
It should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on the issue and made significant progress towards a deal that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also provides assistance for property owners, who are having problems paying.
The government should negotiate new instalments in the case of mortgages it is going to redeem, while reducing the monthly payments of debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: A psychological help
According to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to achieve.
“And that’s because we don’t know what the mechanism and the price of the problem asset buyback will be.
This point will be decisive in deciding on the splitting of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now, or early next week, is not, according to Marek, so important.
“It is much more important that Congressmen agree, starting this week, that they support this plan and that we dedicate it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, which envisages the adoption of the plan, is most important at this time," Marek said.
A struggle pushed to the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you, how to choose
While virtually all mobiles can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can call.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only one phone.
However, there is sufficient reason to get an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy an expensive high-end gramophone for the house to put on the new album by Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there are stacked vinyl records in your shelves, with art rock, jazz or blues, you at least probably dream of such a gramophone.
The same goes for music while on the move, namely compressed music, to put it simply - music in MP3.
Here too, there are categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a reader, just as a Pink Floyd fan would struggle to support headphones bought for twenty crowns on the market.
These are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The life of the batteries is also decisive
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are features unknown, of course, to most mobile phones.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, telephone calls and texting, it is able to play music and movies, record the latter, it has a camera of varying quality and can, for example, be used for navigation.
And if you take into account smartphones and communicators, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no refrigerator knows how to grill meat and no television will take photographs, we are witnessing practically a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without disadvantages.
The more features you use, the shorter the interval between two reloads.
And playing music is one of the most important energy goinfres.
There are few mobile phones that are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases this figure is significantly lower.
In this respect, music players (especially the most rudimentary ones) perform significantly better.
In the case of cheap mobiles, expect that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, you happen to call from time to time, get, to be sure, a second recharge for work - this is valid even for the more expensive devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players, which are capable, as a result of recharging, of continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least performing.
Another problem occurs when recording music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be connected directly to the computer, without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to do it without reduction, given the tiny dimensions of the memory cards used in mobile phones.
As far as drives are concerned, you do not need, except for iPod, any software.
Simply fill, through the USB connector, the music device from the computer.
Most mobiles and readers will create a media library themselves, classified by the name of the performer, the title of the album, the style, or by the judgement of the user.
Some devices only display an index with a tree structure, like the Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobiles have more know-how
When choosing a specific device, focus on the battery life, memory capacity, sound quality and output type and, of course, ease of control.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you are going to listen to it for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile reading the MP3s.
Virtually all mobiles are capable of this today.
You don’t even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or player is able to read.
Everyone can play MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will have exactly this format.
It is one of the most popular formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also play music in WMA format.
The AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods), meanwhile, is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
Just visit, from the mobile phone, the corresponding operator's web pages (or those of another provider) and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to purchase a musical mobile.
The offer of the operators is unfortunately miserable and it is limited, in most cases, to fast-made radio tubes.
The prices are not the lowest either.
Nevertheless, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether by GSM, the internet, or even the wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people still carry their motives on themselves.
Whenever you want to listen to something, you just have to take the phone out of your pocket, while you have forgotten your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you still have headphones or a handsfree with connection.
If not, you can use the built-in speakers, which have practically all mobiles, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of musical mobiles is their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three to four thousand crowns, you can have an already very suitable walkman.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the lack of output for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best phones and the best equipped, also provided with an entrance for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having easy control.
Really anyone manages to ensure the control of the most rudimentary readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest (cf. our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the similarity of the command to that of a cassette station, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a randomly connected mobile internet, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g. the Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable memory cards (the M2 type, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
The basic models support in principle only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive do it even with 8GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, a Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, choose specialized walkman mobiles (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and thus the ease of the control is close to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose mobiles in the walkman series have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that has gone the farthest in this area.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a longer battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours), is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the brands mentioned above.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Probably.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force traditional operators to lower prices.
It may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> (Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher here than in the rest of the Union, confirmed this.
Thus, following the last steps of the European Commission in the field of the regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of Czech mobile operators cheaper than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really want to get into the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that is well above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, the chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), who has repeatedly said that in the Czech Republic there is no room for another operator, choruses with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with its own network is apparently no longer very lucky (in fact, now it would be difficult to find frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a considerable drop in prices, to which the traditional operators also had to react.
Yet, even before party troubles such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market, voices similar to those we hear today were heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator managed to win over 100,000 customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let’s add that behind the Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which among other things owns the U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order for them to operate efficiently, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high costs of building, operating and maintaining the mobile network.
This is how virtual operators around the world are profiling themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by a limited service offering.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in the UK at least twice as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity shot.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
"Real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work also in our home.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the offer of services."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
“We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very encouraging.
The launch of Mobilking will instead take place in other countries in our area," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible to prevent a potential competitor from appearing.
The GTS Novera Group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of corporate customers, has not hidden, for a long time, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
“We are very keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to move forward in the negotiations,” said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
The future may be promising.
According to unofficial information, it seems that we might be able to host the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for now, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
“Right now, we don’t think there’s room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with others very specific.
At the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this field has contacted us," mentioned Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of the press department of Telefonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators are also concerned with the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová said in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet registered a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
“It is practically excluded that a virtual operator will appear on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited time frame, we should have a concrete agreement now.”
Instead, Vodafone is focusing its attention on fulfilling requests to get its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared fees and infrastructure.
This is what, in our view, means the most input from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to set up a common network for fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities: in line with operators
The approach of the mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and therefore to a decrease in their profit.
So what is the point of facilitating the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know how to get along like thieves at a fair. The chicane that accompanied the creation of the U:fon also testifies to this.
The biggest apparent pressure on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, when the U:fon was created, was that exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by information available to the public from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> web pages.
Nowadays, U:fon lends itself to serve as an argument for not accepting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová remarked on this: "Mobile market competition has also recently been amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject it, and especially its services, to high demands."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems bewildering.
However, it is not just the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
However, the latter adopted, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached at the moment, because the offer of potential stakeholders did not a priori present enough interest for conventional operators," said Kristián Chalupa of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS's Department of External Relations in response to our question.
A declaration made in this way would not be surprising on the part of operators' representatives.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, also take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, such a statement is more than confusing.
Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual operators are normally present, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to a lower price of mobile telephone services."
However, pushing for an honest functioning of the market and lowering prices is apparently not in the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
What is indeed shocking is the almost touching concord of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, arises quite naturally.
In the same way, a gasoline price strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to chance and the hard fight of competition.
"The Office has not identified any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this respect, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore no one has a corresponding increased responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably even lacking in the telecommunications regulator," Chaloupa said in its statement.
One of the many points of disagreement is the interpretation of the dominant position in the market.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications constitutes a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts propose a different view: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained each time.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
This is how it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators visibly proceed in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including the company GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Putting responsibility back on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common turn in communications, through which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes the hands of the case.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to pass through the recent enactment of the Telecommunications Act an expansion of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>'s powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the UOHS must know this very well, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can work.
That said, the operation of a kind of pseudo-virtual operators, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile phone services, but these are only partly public.
In most cases, there are companies dealing with multi-level marketing.
Specific mobile telephone services are offered, for example, by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually reach only elected officials.
The magic trick consists in the fact that the company makes in front of the operator figure of a classic company customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she gets special (and other) price offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If what you are talking about were to happen, it could be a violation of the contractual conditions that we are examining and that could result in a stoppage of the collaboration with the company in question," Martina Kemrová replied to our question on this issue.
Nevertheless, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such activity did not reach even those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
No operator, however, opposes such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them non-negligible benefits, and, at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them in any way with their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are only used by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the manner of ordinary customers of mobile operators.
But that is precisely what should seem strange to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
In addition, another question arises at UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It must be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has relatively broad powers to disclose such an activity, and if it does not wish to be content with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would occur, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a considerable decrease in the price of services.
However, in practically all countries where virtual operators appeared, conventional operators tried sometimes more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, if not too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it was precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies intervened in the developed countries, which defended not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both through formal measures and informal pressure, they ended up creating a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are treating this issue in the manner of a hot potato that is discarded by passing it on to a nearby target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more than profitable in these cases.
But let's not throw the handle after the axe.
If the behind-the-scenes information tells the truth and a virtual operator will soon appear with us, the Czech mobile market may get back in motion.
If one of the operators has agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to remain impassive in the face of rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
