Passengers can purchase a coupon 30 days or 90 days (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and have it both registered on their smart card in the information points and offices of the Dopravn<0xC3><0xAD> podnik (the Transport Agency), located in the metro stations Muzeum, M<0xC5><0xAF>stek, Nádra<0xC5><0xBE><0xC3><0xAD> Hole<0xC5><0xA1>ovice, Ra<0xC5><0x9B>lis, And<0xC4><0x9B>l.
From yesterday, there is also the possibility to buy the coupons by internet on the web pages of the Dopravn<0xC3><0xAD> podnik: www.dpp.cz.
More than four hundred people took advantage of the service during the morning.
Those who will start using the online store can definitely forget about the counters in the subway stations, where they had to hitherto trample with impatience in long queues in order to get paper tickets.
Indeed, they will buy their coupon online and it will be saved on their Opencard card in one of the thirteen M<0xC4><0x9B>stská knihovna (municipal libraries).
"In these points of contact, there is at the disposal of passengers a ticket office with trained staff, who will help those interested with the purchase by internet and, in addition, will record the coupon they bought on their card," said project spokesman Martin Opatrn<0xC3><0xBD>.
In addition to the libraries, it will also be possible to register the electronic coupons on the Opencard in vending machines installed in the vestibule of several metro stations.
What do these distributors look like?
They are red, reminiscent of the ticket composting machines and passengers may have noticed them already in the metro stations Roztyly, Bud<0xC4><0x9B>jovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
