Sudetenland is calling for a referendum in the US
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans demanded that <0xC5><0xA0>umava be integrated into the United States.
This is the result of a letter filed in the collections of the Jiho<0xC4><0x8D>eská v<0xC4><0x9B>decká knihovna (The Scientific Library of South Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to at least live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of Sudeten Germans allegedly addressed the President of the United States with such a desire.
This is the result of a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now stored in the collections of the Jiho<0xC4><0x8D>eská v<0xC4><0x9B>decká knihovna.
Germans from <0xC4><0x8C>esk<0xC3><0xBD> Krumlov in the letter asked the US president not to allow "<0xC5><0xA1>umavská <0xC5><0xBE>upa" (region of forests south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We understand the situation well and want to be really sure that the words proclaiming that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," the letter, signed "People who care about the fate of the <0xC5><0xA0>umava," reads.
Since the rally with Czechoslovakia is supposedly only promising - knowing the Czech national character - of brutality, disrespectful attitude, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take in his hands the protectorate of the <0xC5><0xA0>umava for now and forever.
“We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a state that is foreign to us, that oppresses and destroys minorities and that has contributed nothing to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of the quarter of a million inhabitants,” the letter reads.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the “Czech oppressors”.
If the president of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans in <0xC5><0xA0>umava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine if its inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given current knowledge of post-war history, seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it illustrates well the expectations of the Sudeten Germans of the time.
While the Czech Germans had at least to foresee that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them admitted such a possibility.
Some expected that the United States and Britain would obtain some kind of autonomy for the Sudetenland.
Others believed that they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in <0xC4><0x8C>eské Bud<0xC4><0x9B>jovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German from <0xC4><0x8C>eské Bud<0xC4><0x9B>jovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When, at the end of the war, he was captured by the English and placed in the Holstein region capture camp, dozens of Czech Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that once they returned home, the Czech would benefit them," Chalupa said.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed that, following the Bene<0xC5><0xA1> Decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
You don't think - you pay!
An emotional campaign will attack drivers
The most expensive road safety action in Czech history.
A way to characterize the emotional media campaign that intends to launch, Wednesday, the Ministry of Transport.
Minister Ale<0xC5><0xA1> <0xC5><0x98>eb<0xC3><0xAD><0xC4><0x8D>ek's office believes it will discourage drivers from dangerous driving behaviour.
This campaign costing 150 million will appear on television, radio, cinema, on the internet, but also on leaflets.
It should discourage drivers from fast driving and alcohol driving.
But also remind them to take the belt before starting.
Above all, it wants to touch the conscience of young drivers, bikers, pedestrians, not to mention professional drivers.
What will appear in the spots?
Especially personal stories that will attack emotions.
This is also reflected in the "bloody" slogan of the entire campaign:
You don't think - you pay!
The phrase "You do not think" is written in capital letters on the license plate.
Then, in a puddle of blood, there's the phrase "You'll pay."
This must symbolize that one can pay for life a moment of inattention.
The spots will "haunt" the spectators until 2010.
The ministry was inspired by similar campaigns in the Anglo-Saxon countries, where one can commonly see images with drastic images of the victims of the accidents.
It believes that this will lead to a decrease in the rate of accidents and the number of deaths on Czech roads.
The spots were prepared by the Euro RSCG agency.
The sugar and whip strategy against drivers
“What works with drivers is the sugar and whip system.
For them, sugar is represented, for example, by saving time, when they grill a red light.
The whip is the threat of a fine or an accident.
The risks must be reminded to the drivers," says Martin Ko<0xC5><0x99>án, transport psychologist at Na Homolce Hospital.
This is how we need information campaigns in the press and especially negative advertisements, the psychologist believes.
In his view, the warning signs for drivers are already less efficient.
"When a static sign that warns of a hazard is installed, it will probably quickly merge with the environment and drivers will no longer notice it," Ko<0xC5><0x99>án said.
Olmert would return almost all occupied territories in exchange for peace
Ehud Olmert, the president of the Israeli Provisional Government, called for the restitution of virtually all the territories occupied in 1967, including the West Bank, East Jerusalem and the Golan Heights, in exchange for peace with Palestine and Syria.
He made the statement in an interview published Monday by the daily Yedioth Ahronoth.
“We need to reach an agreement with the Palestinians, which means it will be necessary to return almost all (occupied) territories, if not all,” Olmert said.
"We will keep a certain percentage of the territory, but we will have to cede to the Palestinians a similar percentage (of the Israeli territory), since without that, peace will not be made," he added.
He admitted that the possible restitution would include East Jerusalem.
"Anyone who wants security in Jerusalem, and especially does not want tractors and bulldozers to crush his feet, as happened to one of my best friends, will have to give up parts of Jerusalem," Olmert said, referring to the two attacks in the city in July, in which several people were killed and dozens wounded.
According to the prime minister, it will be necessary to find "a special solution for the Temple Mount, the sacred and historical places" located inside the Old City.
“Anyone who wants to maintain Israeli sovereignty over the entire city will be forced to integrate 270,000 Arabs.
It won’t work,” he said later.
Retirement from the Golan Heights
Olmert also called for Israel's withdrawal from the Golan Heights, which he said was a prerequisite for concluding a peace agreement with Syria.
However, this would also require some efforts on the part of Damascus.
“I am not proposing to make peace with Syria solely on the basis of a Golan retreat,” he said.
“The Syrians know very well what they will have to give up to get the Golan.
They will have to renounce their current relations with Iran; they will have to renounce their relationship with Hezbollah (Shiite movement); they will have to renounce the constant support they give to terrorism by Hamas (Shiite movement), Al-Qaeda (terrorist network), as well as that of Jihad (holy war) in Iraq.
Questions that arise after the accident: Are stewards in the car illegal?
The law ignores them; walking in a long-distance coach is forbidden
In the context of the tragic accident of the Student Agency bus near Padua, Italy, the question arises whether stewards and passengers can move inside the bus during the journey.
"If you want to comply with the law in a strict and formal way, the activity of a steward is contrary to the law on road traffic," said Transport Ministry spokesman Karel Hanzelka.
The accident in question, in which a 22-year-old hostess died, was apparently caused by the driver of a truck that crossed the way to the bus.
The girl was sadly sitting next to the driver, on the most dangerous seat of the vehicle, although she had two other seats at her disposal.
However, the bus can have an accident, or even brake abruptly, also when the steward serves the coffee or distributes the newspapers.
What matters is whether the coach is under its technical data sheet equipped with standing seats or not.
If this stand-up equipment is not approved, passengers must remain seated.
The Student Agency long-distance coaches do not have standing seats; this was confirmed in Aktuáln<0xC4><0x9B>.cz by the director of the company Radim Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura.
"This is an issue that we have dealt with with the ministry and, in the beginning, it forbids any movement of passengers.
Then they canceled it and we got passengers to go to the toilet during the trip as long as they have their own seat,” he said.
The law ignores the steward.
"There is no unambiguous legal interpretation of the role of steward - no legal prescription takes care of that role.
On the other hand, no legal requirement prohibits the carrier from offering services.
The law on road transport only knows the term "vehicle receiver"; it does not define its rights and duties," spokesman Hanzelka adds with more ambiguity.
On the contrary, Josef Pokorn<0xC3><0xBD>, the director of the Road Traffic Department, believes that the law adequately addresses the problem.
“It all depends on whether the coach has in its homologation the permission to offer standing seats.
It’s all in there,” he said.
The coaches are divided into urban, where there are standing places and a limited maximum speed, intercity with standing places and a higher permitted speed and long distance coaches without standing place with the highest permitted maximum speed and seats equipped with seat belts.
As in the plane, says an expert
Jaroslav Ho<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD>n, an expert at BESIP (road traffic safety) on safety in transport, does not see the movement of stewards on board as a major problem.
"In regular traffic, there is no danger. The situation can be compared to that of service in airplanes.
There, too, it is not sure when turbulence will occur and the air hostess may hit her head."
“Now, in the event that the coach braked abruptly, the laws of physics would obviously be valid.
In the same way as in an urban bus or tram.
The carrier must manage the safety of stewards through internal requirements," he said, adding that from the point of view of the law, the issue is not resolved.
Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura is ready to remove these services
Student Agency is the only coach company to offer steward services.
He hires two hundred.
Even after this accident, the director does not consider their profession as a risky profession.
"However, as soon as I feel that this is a risky trade, I will remove it.
Passengers can receive their coffee and newspaper on board.
It would also reduce costs,” he said.
The concern for safety is the reason given to the absence of stewards in his vehicles by the director of the Asiana Alexei Litvine, which ensures, in comparison with SA, a very small number of lines.
"We don't have hostesses, we have opposed them from the beginning.
Sooner or later it will end in a fatal accident," he told T<0xC3><0xBD>den.cz a year ago.
A huge tragedy has happened
A young hostess from the Plze<0xC5><0x88> region, who had been working for the company for two years, died in the accident on the Naples line.
A Slovenian truck probably left the emergency stop strip without using a blinker and blocked the way to the bus.
The driver of the latter trying to avoid him by means of a sudden maneuver, but he scoured him from his right side.
Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura refuses that the two seats reserved for the rest of the stewards have been sold.
"In the case of long-distance lines, it is not possible to reserve these seats, they are blocked."
The company intends to file a complaint against the driver of the truck.
For the compensation of the girl's family, the agency will not wait for the court's judgment, but with regard to financial compensation, it also relies on the culprit.
A change in the law?
Not in sight
An amendment to the law, which has been in the process of being drafted for more than a year by a group of thirty experts from the Ministry of Transport, could provide clarification on the travel of stewards on board the bus.
"Now, it has not reached any conclusion on this point.
In fact, she is not too interested in buses, but rather in the points system, the maximum speed on the highway and the use of the mobile phone at the wheel," says expert Ho<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD>n.
"The Ministry of Transport does not consider the activity of stewards as something that would fundamentally endanger the safety of passengers," said spokesman Hanzelka, adding that the control of the safety of coaches is under the control of the police and the Office for Safety at Work.
The hopes of the Düsseldorfers are based on Frankfurt.
There was no shortage of great words in the letter from the WestLB Steering Committee to the employees of the house.
A merger of the entities of the Düsseldorf financial institute with the Frankfurt Deka-Bank could create the "central financial market institution of the financial group of the Sparkasse", according to the letter made public on Monday.
WestLB would bring a "skills pool" coupled with sustainable productivity in such a case.
All in all, such a relationship could be the decisive start to further concentrations in the Länder's banking sector.
This is what it looks like when a steering committee wants to demonstrate its ability to act in difficult times.
Because WestLB, wounded, is still under heavy pressure.
It was not only the European Commission, but also the Federal Financial Services Surveillance Authority that, only recently, made it clear to the government of the Land of North Rhine-Westphalia that time was running out in the search for a future solution.
However, there has been talk for some time already - also on the Frankfurt side - of a relationship of some form between the bank Deka, which knows the customers of the Sparkasse from their investment funds, and WestLB.
The head of the Deta-Bank Franz Waas made it clear at the presentation of the figures for the semester at the end of August that he saw no sense in the merger of the house on the Mainzer Landstrasse with a bank of Land, either Helaba or WestLB.
However, the board of directors of the Deka, half of which is supported by the banks of the Länder and by the groups of savings banks, has instructed the steering committee to conduct talks with WestLB with a view to joint commercial activities.
It could then be the debit of the financial market, or parts of it.
However, the talks have only just begun, it is said in the financial centre.
This is not the first time that the Deta-Bank, which, with its 3,000 employees, has one of the largest employers in the Frankfurt financial centre, comes into play when it comes to the consolidation of the savings bank sector.
In 2003, it was believed for a while that the Deta-Bank could merge with the Rhineland-Palatinate State Bank and the Halbab.
However, nothing emerged from this ternary bouquet.
As soon as the plans had been made public, the government of the Land of Hesse had decided against any participation of the Hellaba in them.
The other two houses did not meet either.
The Bank of the Land of Rhineland-Palatinate was attached instead to the Bank of the Land of Baden-Wuttenberg in Stuttgart.
But there have always been new deals on the regrouping of the Deka-Bank with Länder banks.
Lastly, however, Günther Merl, chairman of Hellaba's board of directors, had spoken out against any commercial strategy of merging with his bank.
Regardless of this, the feeling seems to be spreading that the regrouping of the various public sector establishments is particularly urgent.
Now that the election to the Bavarian Parliament has passed, a union of the BayernLB with the Baden-Wuttenberg State Bank could come to fruition in the first place.
For Helaba, this is not particularly good news.
If the pressure for further mergers should increase, the potential partners are gradually escaping.
In the South, it would now be a junior partner, although it has hitherto withstood the crisis better than the banks in Munich and Stuttgart.
The Hesse-Thuringia savings and transfers group, which owns 85 per cent of Helaba's capital, on the other hand, pulled a lock at the beginning of the year on any union with WestLB.
The NordLB would remain to the rigour.
Such geo-strategic reflections, however, reflect only one facet.
Another aspect raises the question of how the different business models of each of these banks can match.
In June, Merl declared that the decisive question, by means of which business model the future capacity of the banks of the Länder should be ensured, had not until then been resolved by the German grouping of savings and transfers.
In the long run, a dismemberment of the WestLb could take place, dismemberment which is obviously not desired here.
This is also what is mentioned in the letter of the incumbent Steering Committee: in any case, a "comprehensive solution" for the establishment would be sought.
How all this will be put in the same basket with the union of some entities with the Deta-Bank remains to be seen.
