Insomnia Nights for Hypo Real Estate Shareholders
The German banking system is relatively stable, the Federal Finance Minister insisted only a few weeks ago.
What a chance that the politician used the word "relatively" and that he slipped that the German banking sector would not be spared by the crisis movements.
This one actually happened this weekend.
The Bavarian real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), on the side of the DAX, gets a credit of one billion from a consortium of German banks to protect itself from market turbulence.
A person in the confidence of the situation told Reuters on Monday that the aid credits are issued up to a sum of 35 billion euros.
Hypo Real Estate would now have to pay interest on the fraction to which it would be entitled.
The money comes from both private banks and public-law banks.
In the background, it is the daughter company Depfa that bears the losses.
The state financier, according to a newspaper article, had refinanced himself in the very short term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which has not been possible since due to mistrust of the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank’s liquidity reserve had been reduced by 95 percent to €2.37 million, and the equity ratio had also declined slightly from 1.6 to 1.45 percent.
Ongoing profits and net profits from financial transactions had fallen to zero compared to the same period the previous year, earnings from the attribution of defined debt and securities as well as the termination of provisions in credit transactions had fallen by more than 70 per cent to EUR 5 million.
And it was only thanks to the significant profits from the reimbursement of the downstream accounting costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa group, as well as the reimbursement of interest under the book of tax procedures and commercial purchases for the Konzern companies that the profit deficit of about 16 percent proved to be moderate.
After its privatization in 1990, the former state financier had initially misspeculated on real estate industrial loans, which had subsequently been affiliated with Aareal Bank.
Because conventional state funding was not profitable enough, Depfa was then more intensively engaged in infrastructure projects and in the financing of private-public-state (PPP) and internationally diversified projects.
On the value of the subsidiary, Hypo Real Estate must carry out amortizations that should have an essential material effect on the calculation of the group’s gains and losses, which remains somewhat unclear.
The fact is that the dividends have been amputated.
Already by 2007, they had been truncated to two-thirds.
Since the acquisition of Depfa, Hypo Real Estate has been a highly important state and infrastructure investor.
It is stronger than other refinancing-dependent institutions in the inter-bank market since it has no client deposits.
With the bankruptcy of investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, the allocation of loans between banks has again considerably dried up, with the banks having accumulated their liquidity.
Hypo Real Estate needs a short-term means of refinancing for a portion of Depfa’s total credits annually – around €50 billion.
According to a statement from Hypo Real Estate, the group's financing need is covered with medium-term credit and the company protected from the influence of international financial markets largely out of business at the moment.
Other sources say the refinancing would be secured through the funds until the end of 2009.
The chairman of the HRE Board of Directors, Georg Funke, explained that the Hypo Real Estate Group should no longer have to use the financial markets in the medium term.
The Federal Bank and the Federal Institution for Financial Services Surveillance (Bafin) assume that the Hypo Real Group's market capacity is now assured.
The bank’s shareholders and creditors have nothing to hope for.
However, given the dynamics and imponderability of the crisis, there is no certainty.
Moreover, it is not unthinkable that funding should not be used in its entirety.
But the opposite cannot be ruled out either.
After the fact that the bank is, according to the latest releases, still at the doors of insolvency Sunday evening, this rescue, to say the least, will not succeed in reassuring the minds either.
The share price fell by 75 percent to EUR 3.30.
Bond prices, on the other hand, are doing particularly well.
While debts in the first place have barely moved, the prices of second-rate loans are declining.
The most affected are mainly the investment funds of the former subsidiary Württemberg Hypo and those of course that have a lifespan beyond 2009.
The bonds of Hypo Real Estate Bank once appeared to be an alternative speculation investment, henceforth their value must be considered dependent on the stability of the international banking system after the net hardening of the banking crisis and the crisis of the very institute that brought the crisis into the establishment by the buyout of Depfa Bank.
As long as the issuing institutions, governments and less affected commercial banks are still ready to support the system, it can be assumed that arrears will be reduced over time.
Or it will happen what no one dares to hope for right now – that the financial crisis can be overcome in the next 15 months.
But in the face of the renewed rumors of partial nationalization, the probability that was approaching security has now become a mere, well-founded hope.
This should set aside sleepless nights primarily for long-term creditors on deciding whether to break away from their commitments.
Short-term investors can still use what they pulled a line on to form a deferral of losses for the next few years on the next capital income tax automatically levied on stock gains.
Sylvana and the secrets of the box in Bento
When 16-year-old Sylvana Hiltrop is due to show up for the first day at Tachibana High School, the girls start to laugh: the German is so "kawaii"!
What does that mean?
Sylvana already knows this word thanks to the Mangas - in her new Exchange Log, she talks about Japan.
"The first day of school in Japan.
What was I excited about?
Already on the way to school I was scared.
