Rats have sensations too.
A rat or a cockroach flees from danger, does that mean they also feel fear?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have sensations.
But how could we verify that he feels the same thing when he behaves the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having so far been able to prove it just as one cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter hard-to-practice terrain because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it kills, flees, or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
However, I don't believe it.
Two aspects of brain structure make transposing our subjective experience to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that the circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the prefrontal lateral cortex (because of its involvement in short-term memory and in the functions of direction and execution).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent in other beings.
At the very least, therefore, for those aspects of our consciousness which depend on the prefrontal cortex, among which the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being is even different from other primates.
Another significant peculiarity might lie in the linguistic nature of Man: much of his existence being related to language, it often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, the animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness were not to depend on language, it would surely influence it, so that animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably differ much from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is also difficult to determine what consciousness can look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, is neither measured nor, because of this particular Hardware, analyzed based on our own experience, then its observation poses great problems for us.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is next to it another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
Animal consciousness processes could be examined without regard to their content, and this is exactly what happened in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially with the example of visualization.
But in this approach followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, we focus more on the nerve correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both can be identical or not.
Interestingly, this approach also highlights the weight of the prefrontal cortex in the realization of the visualization.
But what does that mean for emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
What we call "fear" is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the localized defense system in the brain (or its aftermath, such as the body's reactions) takes over from vivid memory.
Thus observed, the emotions are closely related to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially humans.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our volatile nature, emerge, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to impute them to others than ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, thinks that sensations from primitive activities arise in the body sensation regions of the cortex and brainstem, as does Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brainstem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could be quite involved in transversal sensations of all kinds.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict it, but I believe that this is indisputable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in men and in rats is likely to be felt as such in both cases: how could one yet check whether rats and men feel the same thing when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach flees danger, but if it feels fear?
In my opinion, similar behaviors are not enough to prove identical experiences.
Admittedly, the nervous comparison helps: rats and men have similar brain trunks, while cockroaches do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem causing the sensations?
And even if we could prove it for humans: how could we prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have sensations.
But I don't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably completely different from ours (since human consciousness relies on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore the emotional behavior than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, there is progress on the nerve plane in that the same thing is measured in rats and in humans.
Since I do not explore the language and consciousness in rats, nor the sensations, I do not know if they exist.
This could be judged as short-term, but I prefer to move forward rather than constantly hitting a wall.
I am indeed an emotionally pragmatic.
