Alcohol offenders will have to install the 'alcolock' system
The Minister of the Interior wants that the driver who has had more than three administrative penalties for blood alcohol, have to install in his vehicle a system that prevents the vehicle from starting intoxicated, or if he does not blow.
The initiative was already announced last June and it now appears in the report of the Minister of State in which this initiative is considered a pilot project that will last one year.
Its goal is the reintegration of the driver by offering courses in road rehabilitation.
The Minister of State in charge of road safety but also the Directorate General of Road Safety and the Institute of Technology for Automotive Safety Foundation will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists arrested for driving more than once in a state of drunkenness, the car resumes.
The alcoholic block would avoid this because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the breath and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not blow before; or when the driver's alcohol level is higher than that allowed.
Its cost is more than 1,000 euros and is borne by the driver.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced up to 65 per cent of offences in the first year of installation.
And in Spain, it is estimated that it could save 115 people’s lives every year.
This measure is based only on administrative sanctions for two reasons: to deal with these behaviours before they turn into criminal offences.
And facilitate its implementation, since the legal reform can be done by ordinary means but, however, the reform done by criminal means requires a reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and functional vehicles already have one on an experimental basis.
Exactly tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative of the Spanish Socialist Party which proposes to install this system in school buses as it was done in France.
