Talking in Sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very awake by telling us something that happened the day before, but to the children who talk during their sleep.
The first time this happens, it may surprise you, but it doesn’t really matter.
It is a benign alteration of sleep called somniloquia.
This is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure there's more than one talking at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life for example associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often linked to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, bedwetting or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As we said before, they can also be associated with very high fevers, stressful situations or overexcitement.
Anyway, this is a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
It may be that he speaks with a quiet little voice, with isolated words, whispers or, on the contrary, with screams, weeping, long speeches...
In case sleepiness becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and in order to get an explanation for this problem.
We have said that it is a benign alteration, which is why there is no treatment unless it is related to another sleep alteration that can be treated (for example, if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
Therefore, look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are more or less violent.
With children who are very nervous and have trouble relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down internally.
This will allow the child to sleep more peacefully.
As soon as sleepiness appears, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
It's useless because he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even if he speaks, he sleeps and rests.
Remember that if he is very anxious several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor or check what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he is saying (which is not usual), don’t be tempted to question him for information.
You will get nothing, because in sleeping, he is not conscious to be able to organize his thought.
What's more, you'll hear what he's saying, but you won't know what he's dreaming about, so pay attention to how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw from it.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to know his secrets.
Not even kidding.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don’t worry, it’s nothing very bad, it’s an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
