Interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec was celebrating its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice as Héma-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And most importantly, he regained public confidence that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood supplies managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In February 1994, the Government of Canada instituted a public inquiry, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations that such a disaster should not happen again.
While Judge Krever was delayed in filing his report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mandate.
As a result of the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
"When Héma-Québec started operations in 1998, only 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec," recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work in the field over the years that followed, we have regained public confidence," she said before proudly asserting that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that "trust is something extremely fragile".
From its inception on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, there were many cases in Europe of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which has held the fort since its foundation in 1998.
“And we didn’t know at all if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports was that when it is not known and a serious disease can result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, the blood of people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980 was refused.
A few years ago, however, it was shown beyond a doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle we applied made sense."
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique for HIV testing appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (TANs), which allow to detect directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus itself and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until then were based.
The NATs have shortened the mute period, which extends between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, says the specialist.
This period was reduced to less than one week.
This substantially reduced the risk that some donors would become infected without knowing it and could not be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before there is a case of HIV transmission through a blood product.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover our health,” says the CEO of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
It is necessary to be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary continues, noting that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for an adequate supply.
“The needs are increasing because the population is ageing.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need red blood cell or platelet refills.
The ageing population also has implications for the blood donor network, which averages only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation."
However, any healthy person aged 18 years and over who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer their blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where malaria is present, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With this 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But members of this network of donors must be renewed as they age and are no longer able to donate their blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to become a regular donor.
Today’s life is so frantic, you rarely find the time to spend an hour giving blood,” Decary said.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for major burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is full of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the banking of our 1,000th sample of cord blood and we plan to take more than 1,000 a year.
We should start proposing for transplants early next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood sampling program as very popular.
"Several mothers are disappointed that they are not able to access it," because Héma-Québec cannot afford to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
