Free opinion - The Orwellian Discourse by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, Senior Vice President, Canadian Barrick Gold Mining.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world’s largest gold company has filed a defamation lawsuit of six million against three authors and a small pennyless publishing house in order to launch a “transparent public debate.”
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of defamation proceedings, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
For, for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publishers of Black Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers backed by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose an amicable settlement that will gag the opposition in addition to scare anyone who dares to look again on the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before public opinion that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Unlike in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada normally take place through the exchange of ideas, not through batons.
It was therefore enough for the mining industry to open up its books, its files and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and rejects the petitions and letters of support for Black Canada's authors.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can both call for a "public" debate while scorning the opinions of that same public?
In the Vice-President's world, it seems that this word refers only to highly paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even critics have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the public that supports Black Canada's authors and publishers does so first and foremost because they reject the brutal way of mining.
This audience is ready to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not as part of what many perceive as a gag-chase (continuing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a formal notice to the authors of Black Canada instructing them to cease the use of the term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver’s surreal discourse, the pursuit of Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, en bloc, the right to cite credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss issues that displease the wealthy companies of this world in a country like Canada, under penalty of repeated prosecution, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
She has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has long managed debates and disagreements and resolved conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate pursuit clearly shows that, contrary to what it claims, it has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the academic world, as well as for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit this kind of abusive prosecution.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republican and Democratic, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic bailout since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has rocked Wall Street for months still needs to be endorsed by both houses of Congress.
In particular, it provides for better control by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right to look at the salaries paid to the managers of the rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, and Republican Representative at the negotiating table Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news just minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great strides towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," Bush administration representative Henry Paulson said.
“Everything has been done in a way to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street,” she said.
“This is the fundamental point: if we don’t do this, the trauma, chaos and disruption on the daily lives of Americans will be immense,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
Negotiations had turned into a sprint in the last few hours for fear of the effect of a further failure on the mood of investors.
The deadline we had agreed was to open markets this morning.
Lately associated with the negotiations, the two candidates in the US presidential election showed rather favorable to the agreement, without failing to express their dissatisfaction that we are forced to reach this extreme.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has attributed to himself the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including one to allow homeowners to keep their homes and one on the salaries of executives of businesses that have been rescued by the state.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary action because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be congratulated on.
But these measures are necessary," he said on U.S. television.
Asked on another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, responded: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The broad lines that I have read [show] that this is something that we are all going to have to digest and with which we are going to be able to move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayer money the dubious, risky and unsellable assets of U.S. financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgages (subprimes) before spreading to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAAs) and resulting in a freeze of liquidity and the dislocation of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican elected officials who thwarted the first draft agreement last week.
They are believed to have emerged from this impasse since Democrats agreed that some “toxic” assets of struggling companies are only insured by the government, rather than bought.
In order to round the corners for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government were to assume losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it recover its bet.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first instalment of $250 billion to which another $100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion is expected to be endorsed by another congressional vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get stakes in the rescued companies that will earn him dividends in case of profit and that he will be able to resell when the turmoil has passed.
The federal government will have the option of delaying forfeiture procedures in respect of the housing attached to the property loans covered by this plan, as well as setting limits on compensation and severance payments to the executives of the affected companies.
The architects of the plan would like to see it put to the vote in the House of Representatives today, and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Yesterday, there were still voices against the bill, both in the Republican and Democratic camps.
“Obviously, Washington doesn’t hear you,” Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told voters.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the way to benefit the taxpayers.”
An entertainer of a small group in Congress dubbed “the caucus of skeptics,” Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred eminent professors of economics, including three Nobel laureates, wrote to us saying: Congress is asked not to rush and carefully consider the way forward,” he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the banking group Fortis for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg was made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas said it was refusing to acquire its competitor in the midst of shipwreck since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US) in the U.S. housing loan crisis.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of Europe’s 20 largest banks and 10 largest insurers.
“This is not money lost,” Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In return, we regain a right to vote in the bank and influence.
It is precisely something that savers and households now appreciate that the times are unclear."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the English Channel, the British government seemed on the way to nationalize another bank badly affected by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all outstanding loans from the Bradford and Bringley bank, including more than 41 billion (US 75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander said yesterday that it would buy the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a committed icon
His beauty in the eyes of azure has long been his asset, some will say his weakness.
Was he freed from the narcissistic mirror, the American actor with a charming smile?
Yes and no.
His modesty, sensitivity and a talent that flowed from the source will have also removed him from the power register that gives birth to the true sacred monsters.
But what a great runner!
Paul Newman, who died Friday at the age of 83 from lung cancer on his Connecticut ranch, remains one of the last icons of American cinema of the booming years.
Less monumental than Brando, to whom he resembled and of whom he was for a long time a kind of rival on screen, more cautious in his play, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the breaking of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often makes beautiful children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925 to a German Jewish father and a Hungarian mother.
From these European roots will be born one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
Without excessive ego, the ultimate mark of quality.
For in him projected a whole country self-made man, the fighter of the Pacific War, wounded in combat, who in the early 1950s studied dramatic art at Yale and then attended the Actor's Studio in New York, before triumphing in the theater, on television, soon in the cinema.
The same man who campaigned for civil rights was also the car driver who finished second at the Le Mans 24 Hours in 1979, doubled with a sex symbol, although a member of a model couple formed since 1958 with actress Joanne Woodward.
The shadowy areas of this secret star, discreet, committed, allergic to the splinters of the show-business, which we have not quite pierced the enigma, also disappear with him.
An honest man, in the noblest sense of the word.
The disappearance of Paul Newman caused the moviegoers dizziness this weekend, as his great roles collide on the black screen of memories.
More than half a century of a seventh American art in perpetual mutation parades through it.
Back in memory the charming cowboy of Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), the young man rejecting his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Cat on a Burning Roof adapted from Tennessee Williams in 1958.
Closer to us (1990), we evoke his sensitive Mr. Bridge, troubled in his old age by a marriage that did not fulfill all his promises.
So many other Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
This boxer Rocky Graziano, delinquent, tormented, violent, unforgettable in Somebody Up There Likes Me, by Robert Wise, a role destined for James Dean, reprised after his death, who really launched Newman in 1956.
This sympathetic villain in the brilliant The Sting, Oscar for best film in 1973.
A bitter and avenging pool player in Robert Rossen's magnificent The Hustler (1961), he will reprise the character on the return in Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, which earned him in 1987 his only Oscar out of nine nominations.
That face through the ages was him.
Just him again.
The times are moving through his path.
Young people know him especially through George Roy Hill's Slap Shot (1977), in Reggie Dunlop, coach of an unorthodox ice hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in The Coen Brothers' The Hudsucker Proxy.
With a final role as the Irish Mafia godfather in Sam Mendes' Road to Perdition in 2003, the loop was closed.
Contrary to several film legends who left the trade early enough, Newman remained in the saddle for a long time, while denouncing Hollywood, its golds, its splendours and its concessions.
The French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier considered it, not without humor, "as a living challenge to the "underplaying" deeming its performances too supported.
The profession has not always been tender for the handsome Paul Newman to whom the roles fell long into the mouth.
However, he played less often the young first than the marginalized: neurotic, alcoholic, bastard or desperate, whose perfect traits reflected drifts and revolts.
As a director, Newman revealed little-known facets of his true modesty.
His Rachel, Rachel, in 1968 (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), with his wife Joanne Woodward in the lead role, drew a fine female portrait of melancholy.
He who lost his son Scott by overdose dedicated his film Harry and Son in 1984, work of modesty and sadness.
Amid the rain of tributes to Newman yesterday, his great buddy and former comrade-in-arms Robert Redford (they had played together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) said, very saddened: "His presence has made my life and this country better."
Generosity, love of existence are vibrant traits of the disappeared actor.
Beyond his career as a legend, a great activist for civil rights, ecology, independent cinema, a challenger to Hollywood's drifts also disappears.
Many will have seen his binette sit on pots of dressing, sauces, cookies and other foods, judging the process of quite bad taste, although gag at first.
Nonetheless, the proceeds from these sales were paid to his Foundation for Distressed Children.
Newman, instead of sitting on his myth, will be committed to the end.
He left a letter to his five daughters containing these sentences: "Always and until the end, your father has been incredibly grateful for his good star.
It was a privilege to be here.”
And it is a privilege for us to have followed the path of such a lucid and generous American artist.
Citizen model, in sum and in addition.
What could Zuschlag & amp; Company do in their invoice factory?
Soon, on 8 October, the hearings concerning the ongoing criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, having resulted in particularly significant damage. Other charges have been held against them, such as forgery and use of forgery.
According to the prosecutor's office, the money from subsidies was spent for personal purposes, while the benefits were justified by false invoices.
The money from the state and municipalities, about 65 million HUF in total, went on the one hand into the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and on the other hand, into the pocket of some people.
Their method, also made public by the investigating authorities, was to collect the money from the subsidies obtained by issuing cost invoices, behind which no actual services were provided and thus the associations never met their commitments.
According to the indictment, much of the bills were false.
For the latter, they procured invoice books at the Józsefváros market, while they manufactured the stamps at Kiskunhalas.
For the names of companies that would appear on the invoices, it was decided, among other things, during the tours in the northern province of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the latter's testimony, he had to spot pensions and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he asked for an invoice, on the model of which they made the other invoices that they were going to submit, among others, to the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the Municipality of the Capital to access grants.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his accomplice András <0xC5><0x90>ri, who, according to our information, was mainly concerned with drafting the files necessary to obtain the grants.
During a "tracking circuit", one of Lados' choices was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, this place ensured the restoration of a group of 90 people, members of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for as many people to occupy this place at the same time.
Similarly, in the summer of 2002, the invoice drawn up in the name of the Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért Foundation, which would later bear the name of Együtt a Harmadik <0xC3><0x89>vezredért, was filled with errors of form and substance.
A boarding house in Badacsonytomaj actually had only three rooms, and a maximum of ten people could stay there, yet the bill mentioned one hundred and thirty guests.
The issuers of invoices with overflowing imagination also fell into excess, when they mentioned the company Pigal Kft, also belonging to the Horeca sector. In their accounting, neither Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért nor Hoppá's name appeared, according to information given to the prosecutor's office.
Gy<0xC5><0x91>z<0xC5><0x91> Farkas, the company's manager, told hvg.hu that when the prosecutor summoned him and showed him the invoices, he knew immediately that they were false documents.
"The name of our company and our tax number were placed in the wrong place on the stamp."
