The Psychology of Over-Billing: Why Do We Spend More Money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the merchandise.
Researchers in neurology and economics at New York University have succeeded in updating the neurological and economic foundations of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distanced in this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that is why they prefer to pay too high a price.
This research attempted to draw up a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played lotto, while the other group took part in a playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) process, the researchers analyzed the active brain domains of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction, an essential element of which is the over-bid of a third, the whole under the brainstem, called the striatum, was moving intensively when the game was lost.
This part of the brain, in addition to several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the flight from the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers continued financial surveillance analyses.
During these sessions, three groups overtook a partner in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and they did so.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they came out winning the game, then they would receive an additional $15, as a reward.
While the third group received that $15 before the auction, the members of the group also lost that money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is that the emphasis was on victory in one group and on failure in the other.
By proving the hypothesis of the neurologists, the members of the team of players "against failure" were willing to bet higher than those made by the control group and the group "for victory".
“These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena observed during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories by now leading to a third explanation.” – Andrew Schotter, professor in the Faculty of Economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: When should we see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned as one of the leading causes of death.
It is estimated that the number of patients carrying the hepatitis virus is one hundred thousand in Hungary, but only seven miles follow treatment, because often the patients do not know that they are carrying the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but the pathogens and diseases generated differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travelers, it is recommended to get vaccinated against A and B viruses anyway. There is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating contaminated foods, usually accompanied by a poor general condition, weakness, stomach ache and nausea.
Then develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible jaundice, the stool becomes lighter and the urine takes a darker color.
Around the world, every year, one million people die from the most serious form of this disease, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that according to estimates, only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients are not known to have the virus, because the pathogenic gene slyly destroys liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattooed people.
Currently, there are 200 million people with chronic hepatitis C worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
30 September is World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing patients from around the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does anyone who believes in God feel less pain?
According to the results of a recent research, religious belief would work as a kind of analgesic, which would have already helped to make the deaths of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British daily Telegraph published an article according to which researchers at the University of Oxford carried out an interesting experiment by analyzing how belief in God could influence human pain tolerance.
As part of this bizarre experiment, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electroshocks, while each of them was observing a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
This analysis is the first in a series of experiments involving academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians from different sectors of the university.
Specifically, the experiment unfolds in the following way: an instrument emitting sparks and diffusing electroshocks is fixed to the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look steadily at two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with hermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the origin of this experiment hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary evoked a kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, focused on its soothing effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time, received 20 electroshocks in four parts successively, while watching either the religious-themed painting or the more general-themed one.
Catholics said that at the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt as if they were "safe", as if they were "cared for" and they were "calm, and peace has invaded them".
At the sight of the religious-themed painting, they accounted for 12% less pain than when they watched Leonardo's work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, thinks that one can achieve the same effects with any other strong image, in atheists, provided that one finds the appropriate photo.
"We should find an image that they react to very positively, such as a mother or father," the psychologist said.
Tom Wright, Anglican Bishop, welcomed the results of this research.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases, it does change our personality," Wright said.
After these excellent results, there remains only the question of what effect would be on the regulation of the pain of the subjects if the believers were shown a Madonna painted by Leonardo or by a painter of the same caliber?
Would the sight of a better quality Virgin Mary result in better results?
You are what you disclose about yourself.
On the occasion of its tenth anniversary, Google says it can be found at the bottom of people's pockets as well as the sky above their heads. It knows where they spent their holidays, what specialists they consult and what their interests are.
However, it is not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, who is one of the influential people in society.
While sceptics draw a parallel to Orwell’s horror vision, they don’t see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main ambition is to gather even more information about its users. This is necessary so that the founders of Google can meet their original goal which sounded like this: "Let's collect in one system all the information in the world!".
According to the Google executive interviewed, after ten years of global work, they are still only at the beginning of their goals of being able to process all the information.
To the question: what will there be in five years? Schmidt replied that he would like Google to be able to answer questions such as "What could I do tomorrow?" or "What work would be best for me?" However, software will only be able to answer this kind of question, simple at first glance, the day they know enough about users.
It is not entirely clear to all internet users that the words used during searches on the internet, the IP address of the computer that launches the search and the pages then viewed by interested persons are precisely listed.
Through the Personalized Search program launched two years ago, users can, for example, store their own search history and can view what they searched for, what they clicked on. Thanks to this, in the long term, Recommendations, program based on the same logic, will be able to give much more personalized answers, and will submit us our products and services based on our previous statements.
What happens if someone uses my data against me, if they look at what my job is? ask users, who are worried about Google's information monopoly.
In most cases, it is the potential power represented by society that can arouse fear, and it is not remorse, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or possibly revolt against power that can arouse a counter-reaction in Internet users.
However, it is a confirmed fact that the terms sought are not only registered, but in justified cases, they are transmitted to a third party, and in this kind of legal case, nothing protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most striking example of recent times is probably the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, during which Google passed on to the Brazilian government the information it had collected on the public page called Orkut, allowing an identification.
Human rights-conscious Internet users were able to breathe a sigh of relief last May, when Google, arm-on-hand with the electronic legal protection agency EFF, proved its right in court before the FBI. According to the ruling, in the future, Google will still not be obliged by any of the constitutional points to disclose information about the FBI's secret request, of any kind.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully obtained some 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms that it had won in relation to the strengthening of the Child Protection Act, passed several years ago. But in the end, it did not succeed in obtaining the lists of searches of private users, nor the entire list of websites and keywords of the last two months.)
Google's judgment is therefore quite contradictory: it is being reproached by those who fear the transmission of their personal data, because they believe that their private sphere and private domain suffer when they start using Google services. Therefore, they attack them in the spirit of revolt that is manifested against the multinational companies proud of their conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its "wildlings" bringing together enthusiasts, activists and enthusiastic computer users who appear in many countries see Google as the next generation of big business, the "trendy corporation", as opposed to its rival, Microsoft, cataloged as an invader of the world because of Windows, and this, although both fight for the same goal.
This can be explained by the fact that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for identification code, does not ask for money for its applications. The documentary code and the package of programs, continuously refreshed, has a much more accessible, younger and cooler effect, in the face of the practice of the official software giant.
The reason may also be that geeks see very accurately the problematic relationship between human rights and the internet, and what the web 2.0, the most proclaimed keyword of recent years, pulls right behind it.
Indeed, the web 2.0 is nothing more than collaboration, the fact that we intentionally leave traces behind us, and that we use the channels of communication at our disposal, and while the dimension of these changes one by one, the essential remains the same: we expose ourselves.
A young person, in general, can keep a profile on several public pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and he can even link these to other services, such as Twinter, or last.fm, listing his musical habits. Then he can link these to a tracking system, such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm recently. These young people can also keep blogs or Flicks on their photos, in which they appear more automatically.
While we can take note of many examples, such as that of the girlfriend who easily understands from the sight of the morning photos, taken by the circle of common friends, with whom her unfaithful friend spent the evening, or that of the company that fired one of its employees private, just for the sincere opinions that this one has written on his blog about top management, we can be totally on the one.
The one who lives an online life is made up of what he shows of himself, and this is how we can define the principle hiding behind the behavior of today's young people.
Anyone who wants to hide something, or at least wants to try to circumvent Google’s monopoly, can do so (starting, for example, with Scroogle, using the Google search system, but at the same time, intentionally leaving no trace).
The number of people who, deliberately, do not register on public pages so that it is not possible to find them, is not the least. The services of Google online, from word processing to image processing, to reading information can be replaced by alternative versions, which are not linked to huge profiles of servers, and which do not exist until today.
Public opinion is waiting, without really hiding from it, for the moment when Google will reveal its true nature.
The company, with its current value of $156 billion, is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion). AdWords/AdSense advertising domains threaten the turnover of advertising agencies, while the services introduced at an increasing speed cause serious computer migraines not only by Microsoft, but by many other programs.
However, critical observers find, next to all of this, contradictions having worrisome effects: for example, the top management of the company has refused, in its entirety, the protests of employees, after it has doubled the price of the Chinese corporate nursery school, after the good results of 2006, and after the company has found their daily multiple restoration too expensive, taken at any time.
According to one of the company's internal rules, the new services are not announced only when they can be used. What is certain is that in the next few months and years, they will move the world medical results on new points. While some think that the complete scanning and archiving project of Google books and magazines can take on such important dimensions that the company will soon find itself in front of the Court.
The fact that Google builds a genetic database can give a good raw material to the next generation of science fiction writers. The novel by the famous Cory Doctorow, written with Orwellian halftones, describes the future in which a man could be approached in a frightening way only through Google data.
