The smart car mimics the bumblebee’s flight
What better method would be to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, if not the imitation of an already existing obstacle detector in nature?
For example, the bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, which took place in Japan, buzzing bees gave the starting strategic idea to Nissan engineers, to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built a mini-robot car, a bio-inspired BR23C self-robotized control system, which it equipped with the qualities of bees, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee forms its own space, oval in shape, which in reality looks very much like our secure protective shell - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the research and development and technological public relations department of the brand.
The faceted eye of the bee plays a primary role, since it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the functions of the faceted eye, the engineers approached the idea of the laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters from the BR23C, assesses distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which turns it into an avoidance manoeuvre right away.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it by an angle sufficient to avoid the collision.
Unlike any existing system, this avoidance maneuver takes place entirely instinctively.
“If it weren’t, the mini-robot car wouldn’t be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantly, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and the most internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the moment the collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must be carried out in the blink of an eye.
In contrast to bees, the difference cannot go upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be of two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that the bees possess to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use the rotational movement, acceleration as well as the slowdown as maneuvers at the disposal of the mini auto robot.
The BR23C uses polymer lithium batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy concentration, which makes them longer in life than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not the processing of data, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism should only process a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it only uses a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
There is no need for memory of a gigabyte capacity, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards designing a technology for instant avoidance, which Nissan estimates will make its way into mass-produced cars in the next decade.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles in his path.
