The written version of the $700 billion economic bailout plan, aimed at repurchasing the banks’ dubious loans, and to be used in multiples, is ready.
In the first round, half of that amount will be spent.
Reuters reports that in new debates lasting until after midnight on Saturday, Congressional leaders have agreed on controversies over the $700 billion bailout.
"We've taken a serious step forward," said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic chairwoman of the U.S. House of Representatives, according to which all that remains is to put the agreements on paper.
The compromise, born from the plan, is backed by the two presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson said in commenting on the results of the compromise that the program will work and be effective, but other measures still need to be implemented. According to Pelosi, it is not a question of saving Wall Street here, but of turning the gears of the economy in the other direction.
The written version of the plan was made public before the opening of Asian markets on Sunday evening at 8 p.m. Washington local time (i.e. Monday at 2 a.m., depending on Central European local time), but did not cause a dramatic rise in the stock markets.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will be the first to vote on the bill in the name of the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008, and then its fate will be in the hands of the Senate.
On Saturday evening, President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi, then the White House also welcomed the news of the deal.
"We are pleased with the progress made tonight, and we highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," White House spokesman Tony Fratto said in a statement.
Moreover, the program diverges from the Bush administration's original proposal that the $700 billion should be spent in one go to buy back the securities for dubious credits.
From now on, a maximum of half of the $700 billion can be spent. The first $250 billion will be issued immediately after the bill is passed by Congress, probably on Monday. This first amount will be used by the Secretary of the Treasury to buy dubious loans from banks, while the use of the additional $100 billion will be left to the discretion of the President.
The program will be overseen by an independent body, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The spending of the second half of the $700 billion depends on a new congressional decree.
Under the law, the Treasury Secretariat will be able to implement a combined strategy: at the same time, it will be able to purchase dubious debts, securities relating to dubious mortgages and mortgages, as well as other types of "toxic" debts.
The department's competent persons stated that the repurchases can take place as part of an auction, but also directly.
The rule gives the companies concerned the opportunity to take part in an insurance program, where the Treasury Secretariat guarantees the tools that cause the concerns, for which the companies have paid a premium equivalent to the foreseeable damage.
Henry Paulson said the law provides the necessary tools to devote $700 billion to the urgent needs of the financial system, whether it is the vast redemption of dubious debts, their insurance, or avoiding the risk of seeing the system leading to the collapse of either major financial institution.
"We will take the necessary steps, to be ready for law enforcement, as soon as it is signed," he added.
On the other hand, bank executives who are in bad shape and waiting for state aid can expect their severance pay, simply called the golden parachute across the Atlantic, to be capped by the government.
Wage caps are mentioned only in specific cases, and the limitations depend on how the Treasury Secretariat offers assistance to the company.
The capping principle means that if the Treasury Secretariat buys back as part of an auction, they will levy a surplus tax on the golden parachute, unless the discredited bank president retires.
Directly after the redemption of the suspicious receivables, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the amount paid to the executives is not exaggerated.
In order for the image to be complete, it must be added that the existing golden parachutes are not modified. The cap only applies to new contracts, this to motivate participation in the plan.
This is the first time in U.S. history that legal caps will be in place regarding the appointments of directors-general, said the chairman of the House Financial Benefits Committee, Democrat Barney Frank.
In addition, the state obtains a right to acquire shares in the banks participating in the plan. In this way, the risk of taxpayers decreases, since they can even be a winner in the case as soon as the economy and with it the saved banks fall back on their feet.
The bill states that in the next five years, the President must submit to Congress a proposal that will rule on how the losses will be returned to taxpayers, from the financial sector.
On both sides, there were obviously those who expressed their doubts about this plan.
That's not why American citizens have mandated us, this doesn't protect taxpayer dollars - said California Republican MP Darrell Issa.
His Ohio Democrat colleague, Mary Kaptur, believes that it is the same people who are pressing for action, as those responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 - reports the Central Statistical Office of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 percent compared to July 2008, while compared to a year earlier, they decreased by 3.9 percent.
As a result of domestic and export price fluctuations, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to those of the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent compared to those of the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices rose only to a lesser extent: 0.1 percent, compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industries were only slightly up 0.1 percent from July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather goods and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 percent), with firstly bags and belt manufacturing with a monthly increase of 4.6 percent, then footwear production with a monthly increase of 2.5 percent.
The higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the manufacturing sector of products and chemical materials (1.6 per cent).
This resulted in deflation in the oil processing sectors (1.4 per cent), the manufacture of electrical machinery and appliances (0.9 per cent), and a minimal increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
Other sectors of the processing industry experienced an increase of between 0.2 per cent and 0.9 per cent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which play a significant role in domestic industrial operations, prices rose 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in gas prices introduced by the authorities since July 1.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account domestic sales of the processing sectors, the most significant increase was in oil processing sector prices (32.4 percent).
In the metallurgical product manufacturing sector, prices increased by 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food, beverage and tobacco production, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price declines occurred in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and appliances (3.3 per cent).
In other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6 per cent to 9.1 per cent.
In the processing industry as a whole, prices increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors surpassed those of the previous year by 18.7 percent.
Among the domestic trade groups and by sector allocation, in August, the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 percent) was initiating profit-on-investment sectors.
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 percent, while those in the energy and materials-producing sectors for further processing did not change from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was seen in the energy and material production sectors for further processing (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was measured at 6.8 per cent, while in the profit-initiating sectors it was measured at 1.4 per cent.
Export prices of the industrial sector, in HUF, rose 1.1 percent in August from the previous month, while they fell 3.9 percent over 12 months.
