Mp3 player pointed at the finger, they put the hearing at risk.
Listening to music at full volume for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission announces, which in a statement released in Brussels, quotes the Scientific Committee's opinion on the unforeseen and recently identified health risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
“From this scientific report, it appears that 5-10% of those who, over a period of at least five years, listen to music at full volume using portable music devices, for more than an hour a day and a week, are at risk of permanent loss of hearing.”
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and full-volume mobile phones may unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably," Kuneva said.
"According to the scientific data - continues the head of the Ue - this is a clear risk and we must react quickly.
What matters most is raising consumer awareness and making this information public.
We must also re-examine the existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can follow up on new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable music devices and the increasing number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
"The scientists-concluding the EU Executive confirm that there is good reason to be concerned, and that the European Commission will now discuss with Member States and other interested parties, what measures could possibly be adopted to better protect children and adolescents, against exposure to noise from portable music devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but there is growing concern about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to limit this data well using solutions such as reducing levels and duration of exposure to noise.
The Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, who listen to music at full volume (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, exceed the current limits on the maximum noise level in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for extended periods of time risk a permanent loss of hearing ability after 5 years.
This is of interest to 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified to around 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
