The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago, with the vote of the House of Representatives, contrary to the $700 billion bailout approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the American economy.
And it is the New York Times of yesterday that confirms that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more divided between its East Coast soul watchman, moderate, favorable to federal institutions as well as to the business community, and its new soul, on the contrary, conservative, hostile to "those of Washington" and to the world of finance, powerful especially in the Central and Southern States.
The very soul, precisely, which made itself felt despotically with the vote I was talking about at the beginning.
However, what has just been mentioned is only one example of the changes, the great changes that the economic earthquake that is underway predicts or already lets go: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and perhaps not only here.
In the United States as in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the phenomena incubated for some time, to the point that, in the new climate, they solidify and reveal themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category of sovereign state, in relation to a kind of re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions that have, of course, close relations with foreign countries, but that, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of individuals and families who live in one country, in one state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically, it is almost only national here.
Political internationalisation seems really out of the question, or does not have much to say: the obvious evidence is provided by the European Union, which, as usual, is divided between the various interests and between the various national strategies, and cannot decide on any common political lines.
And so it is from the government of each state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and stimulus plans, new rules, and above all an affection of credits: when we go through a difficult period, it is only the states that have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to put things back in place.
They also have the necessary resources and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of inestimable value, elements of which no market or international organization can ever dispose in a similar way.
This new emphasis of the nation-state crisis is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever-greater importance that the more recent economic developments of the economy tend to attribute to a factor quite linked to this element: territoriality.
. Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we have now entered the realm of the network, of the increasingly sophisticated technology, of the non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized at once that our future will have to settle its accounts more and more with the things that are not enough material, such as water.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another of the earth, but which are absolutely linked to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
Hence, who is sovereign, certainly has more cards than he who is not, that is, he who has the misfortune to live in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty which, however, provides for a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably said Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to handle the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, economic species that have proved inadequate and full of shade.
And moreover, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even troubling: a discredit, a suffering, an image of inadequacy, a feeling of remoteness that tends to involve the entire class of directors in a growing number of countries of the West.
Thus the conviction of the various classes increases even more, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now at their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be ever more alien to the opinions of the majorities.
