Students victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for a room.
The market for student rentals is not experiencing a crisis
According to the latest survey of the Sunia, the tenant union, renting a single room can cost a student, up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding entire categories of young people from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that families of origin have to support," explains the head of Sunia's research office, Laura Mariani, "in these cities, the high demand from students has distorted the market so much that a process of widespread increase has started for them.
In most cases, rental offers also involve a series of violations: free, unregistered, rent-free contracts, sub-leases.
For the Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of the taxation, are necessary to calm prices.
Reading in detail the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, we go from 650 euros minimum (zone Bande Nere), to an average value of 800 (zone Lambiate, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (zone Vittoria)
In Florence, a bed costs on average, 350/400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, and from 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in the areas near the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), we ask for about 600 euros for a single, 450 for a bed in a double.
Slightly lower values (550 euro for a single) for areas close to the other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecitt<0xC3><0xA0>).
One can only save if one moves away in the peripheral areas: 300 euro for a bed, and 450 for a single in the area Predestina, Centocelle or similar.
In Naples, for a bed you need 300/400 euros, for a single one you spend 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari, for bed, it is necessary to count 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they have a major importance in the urban economy.
Finally, in cities such as Perugia, where rents are often taken by extra-community students, there is a subsequent anomaly: the rent charged to foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradiso, the cities are moving the historic rooms.
Historical cinemas close in favor of multiplexes.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the major Italian urban centers, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of large multi-rooms, and the death of consumptive mono-rooms in the central areas of cities, is one of the major events that seems to us inescapable and indisputable; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical places and loaded with memory, "it is as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we have shared a bit of path and so many emotions" observes the director of the cinema Nuovo Paradiso, film that offers Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of the Jury of Cannes, and who told the poems of the province of Cannes, and always.
The figures provided by Anec, the main trade association, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 cinemas of the traditional type have closed, and it is the theaters of the main cities that paid the most: 10 fewer in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 fewer in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Emilia-Romagna leads with 82 lost mono cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence that confirms t that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has developed in an irrational way," observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it should still guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a room closes in a city, these frequenters are not necessarily all willing to go to the multiplex.
Not to mention the failed deliberation of credit in favour of traders: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between 16 and 18 million euros a year.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about these closures, decided to resolve the situation through the signing of a protocol between the City Hall and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote mono cinemas in historic centers and on the outskirts.
Among the regulations, there are measures of tax facilities in favor of managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the area with limited traffic, and will have special rates for parking and in certain parking lots.
"This is an initiative that I like," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by putting in place other measures.
However, it is obvious that in order to contrast the super power of multiplexes, traditional rooms also need to improve the quality of sound and image, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradiso" that I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have lived so much shared emotions, I turn to the other side not to see the panels blackened by the dust.
