When energy is born from waves, now the big ones are launched.
This is an enormous deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet's surface and now the world's major energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources that colossus like Chevron have set their eyes on, and are now trying to get their hands on.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years now, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now the environmental authorities and the new increase in oil give a great boost to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world’s electricity demand could be covered by sea-swell operating systems.
That would be twice the amount produced by nuclear power plants.
And besides, there would be the currents and the tides.
Colossians in the attack.
The first company to focus on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a facility in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it seemed like a real revolutionary step.
Two years from now, more and more candidates among these companies that have always been dedicated to traditional energy are focusing on marine energy.
“Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies,” a spokesperson for a company associated with the American oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, “and is evaluating opportunities to cooperate with us.”
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a deliberate permit by the U.S. Energy Commission, necessary to give rise to a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially considering that precisely in Alaska, the U.S. continues to extract oil, and recently President Bush has set up a project for new excavations.
In addition to Chevron, there are Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey, which travel the path of energy from the sea, and the sums invested to date, although their details are not known, according to observers, indicate growing interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts talk about a technology still in its infancy, due to the fact that marine energy does not dispel fears about environmental impact.
At present, systems such as those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small, and do not seem to create a big problem for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, it is necessary to use technologies with a higher environmental impact.
"And the choices are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the sludge up and down, is converted into a hydraulic pressure of the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure causes a turbine to rotate, which in turn powers a generator.
The energy is sent to the shore through submarine cables.
At the moment, we have four such systems in the project phase, pending a single federal approval and some of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces energy for a shopping mall and parking lot using six submarine turbines from New York’s East River.
The movement of the water during the tides, rotates the blades of the turbines, creating a rotational movement that powers a generator.
Verdant has announced that it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to draw energy.
After the waves, the tides.
Particular interest, they say at the Institute for Electrical Energy Research, deserves right now, the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable from wind, sun, or waves, and therefore more reliable as an energy source.
And it is precisely on tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others, look to the coast, invested $7.5 million in 2008 and expects investments of up to $35 million in 2009.
